## Core CSM Competencies This Case Demonstrates

| CSM Competency | What This Case Shows | How to Apply It |
|--|--|--|
| **Technical Credibility** | You understand IAM, MFA, access management, and AWS recovery procedures well enough to diagnose *why* the incident happened | Customers trust CSMs who don't panic during crises and can explain what went wrong. If you can do that, they'll listen when you propose prevention work. |
| **Adoption Risk Identification** | You spot when infrastructure decisions create risk (MFA on personal device = single point of failure) and flag them *before* they become incidents | Don't wait for incidents to happen. In your customer reviews, ask: "What would break our business if it failed?" Then audit whether they're protected from that. |
| **Retention & Expansion Logic** | You understand that customers who've had incidents are either more likely to churn (if the vendor abandons them) or more likely to expand (if the vendor helps them improve) | The incident is a fork in the road. Your response determines which path the customer takes. |
| **Operating Rhythm & Governance** | You structure customer engagement so that incidents are caught early (access reviews, change management) or prevented entirely (governance processes) | Build a calendar where you're continuously checking for hidden risks. Don't wait for the customer to discover them. |
| **Stakeholder Alignment** | You translate the technical crisis (MFA unavailable) into business language (access control failure, regulatory exposure, operational risk) so that different stakeholders understand why prevention matters | In the remediation conversation, speak to the CIO about operational resilience, the CFO about compliance risk, and the CEO about customer trust. |

