## Common CSM Mistakes (What NOT to Do)

### Don't use this case to scare customers
"You have MFA on a personal device? That's dangerous. Look at this case study." 
This approach creates defensiveness, not openness.

Instead: "I studied this case. It made me think we should audit your access controls 
together. Not because you're doing anything wrong, but because this is where real risk lives."

### Don't present the RCA without proposing solutions
"Here's why this happened" feels like blame.  
"Here's why this happened, and here's how we prevent it together" feels like partnership.

Always lead with the path forward.

###  Don't assume your customer hasn't thought about this
Many customers have already realized the gap. They might not have the time/skills to fix it, 
but they know the problem exists. Don't position yourself as the hero who discovered it. 
Position yourself as the partner who helps them solve it.

### Don't make this about your platform
"This is a risk with AWS" or "this is an identity management problem."  
This is actually an operating model problem. Your role is helping the customer build better 
operating models, regardless of which platform they're using.

